# Local UI + Kubernetes port-forward (preferred dev pattern)

When a stack has a web UI and remote services (e.g. production in Kubernetes), **prefer** a Docker Compose pattern with two clear profiles:

1. **`local`** — run the full stack locally (backend, Redis, UI, agents, etc.) for end-to-end local development.
2. **`ui`** — run **only the UI** (dev server / hot reload) in the compose graph, with everything else reached via **Kubernetes `kubectl port-forward`** (or equivalent) sidecars so the browser talks to real prod-like APIs and data.

## Why

- Fast frontend iteration without rebuilding or redeploying the whole cluster.
- Realistic integration against live backends when you need it.
- Avoids naming the profile `prod` (which confuses “running prod” vs “pointing at prod”). Prefer short names like `ui` over verbose ones.

## Canonical reference

**subnet-signal** implements this:

- `docker compose --profile local up --build` — full local stack.
- `docker compose --profile ui up --build` — `frontend-ui` + kubectl forwards to cluster services (e.g. backend, Redis, Grafana, Prometheus).

When adding similar setups elsewhere, mirror that naming (`local` + `ui`) and document host ports in `.env.example` / README.
